    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "If you change the byzantiumblock from `0` to `1`, it means that you are activating byzantium rules one block later. So when importing block `0`, byzantium is not active. And that leads to a different stateroot when executing the transactions. Thus, when the calculated stateroot is compared to the stateroot that the block header \"claims\", we find that \"nope, this block/header doesn't produce the stateroot that it says it does\", and we reject it. \r\n\r\n\r\n> Why use 0 as height for ByzantiumBlock, ConstantinopleBlock and other fork height in Test? Why couldn't use a none-zero value?\r\n\r\nWe could, but then the tests would have to be regenerated with different expectations. ",
